Superintendent Voice Mail Message to RSU 20 families:

Good Morning, this is Chris Downing, Superintendent of RSU 20.

We appreciate your participation in last month’s survey. We are using the survey results along with Maine DOE and Maine CDC guidelines to work toward the finalization of our Learning Continuity Plan.

In order to implement a plan that works for RSU 20 families, we need your valuable input.

Please review our Learning Continuity Plan and answer a few specific questions regarding your student’s return to school.

The link to complete this important survey is on RSU20.org and can be found on our Facebook page: https://forms.gle/8JxB5zu9zjVyN1SE7.

The results of this survey will be shared with our school board to inform their decision on our return to school in September.

Thank you, take care, and be safe.

Chris Downing
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
March 15, 2020
Message from Superintendent Chris Downing Re: School Closure

Schools will be closed starting Monday, March 16th and will remain closed through Friday, March 27th. I wanted to communicate this news to you as soon as possible so you may begin planning for child care and other concerns that will be raised by this decision. On or before Thursday, March 26th, a decision on a potentially longer closure will be made based on the facts available at that time.

This closure is in response to the call by medical professionals to implement practices of social distancing and is not the result of any suspected or confirmed cases of COVID-19 in our community,

Thank you for your continued support of our students and our schools. More information will be mailed out tomorrow.

Sincerely,
Chris Downing
Superintendent of Schools

Per the Maine CDC:

Those with flu-like illness should stay home for at least 24 hours after they no longer have a fever, or signs of a fever, without the use of fever-reducing medicines. They should stay home even if they are using antiviral drugs. If a child comes to school sick, they will be sent home. Please do not send your child to school if they are not feeling well.

Please remind your child/ren to wash their hands frequently and to cover their coughs.

post_text:
NEW VACCINE REQUIREMENT

Meningococcal disease is a serious illness caused by a bacterium. It can cause meningitis, which is an infection of the brain and spinal cord, and it can also cause blood infections. The infection can cause death or lifelong disability.

What is the new meningococcal vaccination requirement?

Starting 2018-2019 school year, all students entering, advancing, or transferring into 7th grade and 12th grade in Maine public and private schools must have proof that they have the age appropriate meningococcal vaccines (MCV4) serogroups A, C, W, and Y.

One dose of MCV4 is required for all students entering 7th grade.

Two doses of MCV4 are required for students entering 12th grade, with a minimum of 8 weeks between dose one and dose two. If the first dose of MCV4 was administered on or after the 16th birthday, a second dose is not required.

If a student entering 12th grade is 15 years of age or younger, only one dose is required.

post_text:
MIDCOAST MAINEIACS UPDATE!
Congratulations to the SDHS Robotics Team, the Midcoast MAINEiacs, for an outstanding job at their UNH competition this weekend. They finished 18th of 42 teams in the qualifying matches, and were selected to be on the #2 seed alliance for the playoffs. They advanced all the way to the final before losing to the #1 seed.

Additionally, they were runner-up for the Industrial Safety award, and earned the prestigious Gracious Professionalism award for help and support given to other teams.

Over the course of the weekend, all of them demonstrated incredible perseverance, leadership, problem solving, compassion, collegiality, and focus, all with an unflagging can-do attitude. So if you see them, please congratulate them for all their hard work!

post_text:
Please Join Kim Laplant and Susan Capwell for a culminating project exhibit by the 7th Grade Social Studies class - Thursday, 6/15, from 6-7pm at the Penobscot Marine Museum’s Merithew House.

For the past six weeks, Kim's students have been working with us in the STEAM Lab on an exciting project, exploring the impact of Penobscot Bay on individuals and communities in our area. They have conducted hours of research, digging into the history, economics, and geography of this beautiful region. They have visited the Penobscot Marine Museum’s Merithew House, further deepening their understanding of the Bay’s past, present and future. Together with their peers, they have created compelling exhibits that share their answers to the unit’s driving questions.

We look forward to seeing you at the June 15th exhibit! We are proud of what these students have accomplished, and we can’t wait for you to see it!
